John Edward: Language Skills Essential for World Citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a zipper of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which have only been reinforced by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community enterprises.
With more than 30,000 schoolchildren across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their schoolchildren and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen careers and their position as world citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a customized school curriculum, we see that world language continues to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It's a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year's recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest passing rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of schoolchildren who studied foreign languages achieved a grade A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students achieved an A grade in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 of those who studied French and 63 of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages now, as subjects, have the same prestige as the STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools' curricula and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission on Professions and Skills in 2014 found that 17 percent of the reasons employees provide why they struggle to fill positions are attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real benefit in the future with such a lifelong skill.
To be able to communicate directly with people from other countries, a multilingual person will automatically place above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double digit percentage, 15 percent.
That's why it's so important to invest in today's children's language learning.
Knowing multiple languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance of getting meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other languages will teach what is considered essential for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest is, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment,that languages are still extremely important for the country's future, and therefore it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
We have to do it.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
